title: Fujifilm X-T20 and X-T10 Base Grip with Manfrotto RC2 QR Plate

description.text:
This is a base grip for FujiFilm X-T20 and X-T10 cameras.
The grip is designed to allow a Manfrotto RC2 quick release plate to be permanently mounted to the camera while still allowing access to the battery and SD card compartment.

By producing the design in 2 parts, it has allowed the QR plate to be mounted (almost) in line with the lens. An added bonus is that it changes your grip on the camera, moving your palm away from the Menu button cluster. The QR plate is also likely to wear, so the 2 part design means you only have to reprint the plate if it becomes damaged or worn.

Please note that the design is based on a very specific Cap Head, Hex Socket machine screw instead of a standard tripod screw. I will be obtaining some standard tripod screws and amend the design in due course.

You will also need 4 20mm M4 Pan Head machine screws and nuts to attach the QR plate to the base.

Notes:

In Simplify 3D I used supports for the recessed bolt holes - 2mm from buildplate only.
My example is printed in PLA. I did try with ABS but got a lot of shrinkage around the battery compartment access hole.

Printed with 6 outlines/shells and 6 top/bottom layers. You can probably get away with less but I used this amount to make it as robust as possible in PLA.

For assembly, push the nuts into the recesses. I then attached the QR plate and did everything up to pull the screw heads and nuts fully into their recesses.
I also placed electrical tape over the nuts to prevent marking the camera base.
Remove the QR Plate. Bolt on the camera and then attach the plate again.

Designed in Fusion 360 by scanning the base of the camera and importing as a canvas. I then created outline sketches that could be extruded and shaped into the base, adding holes and recesses where needed.
I already had the QR as an F360 component so was able to import into my design and create the through-holes where needed.

description.text:
Eigentlich wollte ich den IKEA-Tisch nur leicht höher legen und den Prusa i3 Mk2S mit Multi-Material-Upgrade unterbringen.
430mm Höhe reichen für die festen Anbauteile dicke aus, doch ist das in 200mm Arbeitshöhe etwas viel Widerstand für die Teflon-Schläuche.
So ist dieser Gedanke erst einmal hinfällig. Aber vielleicht findet jemand Gefallen daran, auf den Ikea-Tisch einfach noch etwas als Deckel aufzusetzen.

Die Füße werden am Tisch verschraubt und haben an den Außenseiten die entsprechende Kontur für den Fiskbo-Bilderrahmen. Dieser kommt hier in der kleinen Ausführung von 40x50 cm zum Einsatz.
In der vorliegenden Konfiguration ist vorgesehen, dass unten an der Vitrine zwei schwenkbare Türen angebracht sind, die sich von einer Position aus einmal nach links und einmal nach rechts öffnen, so dass der Eingriff von links und von vorn gleichzeitig möglich ist. Die anderen Seitenwände sind starr eingesetzt.

Denn dort, wo ein Scharnier angesetzt ist, muss im Fuß natürlich der Freiraum sein und dort ist dann der Verschluss auch etwas kürzer.

An den oberen Haltern hab ich die Position insgesamt nach unten versetzt, die Bohrungen sind aber an der gleichen Position, als würde man die große Vitrine aus 2 Tischen mit 50x70er Rahmen aufbauen. So geht hier wieder die Bohrschablone, und sollte man es sich irgendwann anders überlegen und will größer bauen, kann man den Tisch oben wiederverwenden und hat keine alten Löcher. Man braucht dann nur die entsprechenden anderen Halter (oder ggf Scharniere).

Insgesamt steht die Kombination dann nur oben auf, ohne mit dem Gehäuse darunter verschraubt zu werden. Durch die überlappenden Kanten an den Außenseiten rutscht es auch nicht einfach herunter.
Kabinett unten, oben der Aufsatz aus diesem Remix

description.text:
PetraPrinter: Z-Axis

I spent a few months on design/build my own printer. Meanwhile I learnt the basics of CAD and 3d-printing itself. The design goals were to build a Prusa-style printer with an enclosure to print high-temp materials like ABS. Although today I would not build this machine this way again, there are still some interesting and somewhat unique solutions that worth sharing. Given these reasons, I'm sharing the files component-by-component instead of the full printer, which has some design flaws.

Whatch the video - [youtube link here]
All OpenSCAD files are available on Github
The PetraPrinter Collection on Thingiverse.

About the parts

I didn't use v-wheel matching rollers. The distance of the wheels was specified by trial-and-error. I find 0.5mm steps were sufficient to find the best fit. The OpenScad design is parametric, you can do the same. Go to github to download/customize. Make sure you print it from ABS or PETG, and use the material's own flexibility to tension the wheels on the extrusion.

Aside of that, it's a very rigid and silent motion system.

description.text:
This is an enclosure for mounting a Duet WiFi controller to a D-Bot or other printer that uses V-channel extrusions as the frame. Its designed to be mounted vertically, maintaining passive airflow over the rear of the board per Duet instructions for cooling. Additionally, a fan can be mounted to drive additional airflow over the board. The enclosure has a hinged lid designed to be able to be opened while the enclosure is up against the extrusions, and a great number of 17mm openings suitable for half inch split loom to protect wire bundles. The enclosure is designed to mount with the USB port and SD card, and other buttons, on the inside of the front rail on the D-Bot, to minimize things sticking outside the frame.

I spent a good bit of time trying to figure out the best arrangement of openings for wiring, and settled on "can't have too many", so there's a lot. I'm working on a plug design to close ones that aren't being used, but so far they've not been reliable when printed with PLA, which I'm trying to resolve before I upload. There's also a 10mm hole on the top edge which I'm using for the wiring to my PanelDue controller, using my PanelDue enclosure here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2486323

The board mounts with short M4 screws to the enclosure. The lid uses 5mm shelf pins like these: https://www.lowes.com/pd/Hillman-8-Pack-5mm-Nickel-Plated-Peg-Shelving-Hardware/999995496

The enclosure can be mounted with two or four bolts to the V-channel. If you use four, you're going to need rounded topped 8mm M5 bolts to fit under it -- cap head, like the D-bot specifies for its other bolts, won't clear the hinge.

The hinge screws shut using a flat-top M4 screw, and a captive nut so it can be opened and closed without wear over time.

If there's demand for it, I can probably modify the end cuts for a Duet Ethernet, but I couldn't test it because I don't have one. I think the rest of the board spacings are identical, though.

Edit:

I've uploaded a second version (v56) of the Body of the enclosure. The more work I'd done with my D-Bot, the less I liked the sharp angle the extruder heater wiring had to take to reach the connectors. (Its annoying that they come off a different side than the power in and bed heater connections, where you're already going to need clearance in the enclosure. The updated one has a small rectangular opening on the bottom where the connections are, so if you prefer to run pin connectors out rather than having tinned-tip wires doing a sharp L to reach them, you can run the extruder heaters out the bottom of the enclosure.

I'm leaving the original (v55) for anyone who wants to keep the bottom "clean" and just squeeze the connections in.

I'd probably recommend v56 though, if you're printing it. Better to have the hole (which you can't see with it mounted) and not use it than decide you need it and not have it.

Update:
I've uploaded a fan grille/cover that matches this: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2834376

My pretty version of an ATX PSU to lab bench power supply. Follow the RepRap ATX to power supply (PSU) conversion guide for directions and warnings.
There seem to be enough PSU conversion cases/fittings here so why did I upload mine:
1.) I like simplicity so no lights and a clean mounting surface.
2.) None that I saw added what I feel is vital and that is an easy to check fuse system on the PSU.
3.) These are for my kids which like to see sparks and burn things up… I like to fuse the PSU under what each power rail is rated so the fuse blows before the box smokes…

The parts I used were banana posts that you can find in any electronic components store. A mini fuse box for an ATV was used for that clean easy to inspect fuse box look. The two screws run through the case and the fuse box to attach the entire assembly. The ATX PSU I buy have to have a large fan and a physical power switch. (1 less thing to buy and wire)

Unfortunately every ATV fuse box I have purchased is slightly different so this would be best used as a reference part. (The ATV fuse box I used is not listed anymore on Amazon, I attached a picture what I found that was similar)

UPDATE 9/9/2017:
I had to make another PSU (and the box I could find was different again) and while doing that I thought I would learn about making a parametric model in FreeCAD that can survive some wild variable changes (See MKII FreeCAD file). The FreeCAD model has a spreadsheet with the parameters to fit any fuse box. (See attached picture for parameter names) It is also a good representation on how to make clean models that won’t break with parameter changes that drastically change the model because it uses Boolean operations that are relational to a geometric loft and not tied to model state. I use the word loft here liberally because in this model it’s just a square blue box set to variable a and b… (FreeCAD blue lines in sketcher are reference geometry)
Old walk through for CAD continues below
END UPDATE 9/9/2017

Steps for making this in CAD
Directions (x = horizontal, y = vertical, Z =towards the PSU)

1.) Sketch a rectangle the size of the PSU Side and extrude (pad) to depth (mine was 20mm) (XY plane +Z extrusion)

2.) Sketch a rectangle on the Z+ surface of the extruded rectangle on step 1 (XY plane with –Z cut)
a. The rectangle size should be centered with a (width – 2thickness, height – 2 thickness)
b. Cut (pocket) the rectangle into the pad in step 1 to (depth – thickness)
c. Note: I used 2mm for my thickness

3.) Sketch the location of the window into your box for the fuses with a cut through all (XY plane)
a. This is dependent on your fuse box

4.) Sketch the padups for the fuse box tabs (Internal face of cover +Z extrusion
a. Again dependent on your fuse box (extrude = depth – thickness of the fuse box tabs)
b. Make sure there is room to get your wires around your pad ups (My design was a little too tight sometimes

5.) Sketch the mounting holes for your fuse box
a. Again dependent on your fuse box

6.) Add the holes for the banana posts on the +Y surface (ZX plane)
a. I make mine r=4.1mm that way I don’t have to worry about drilling them out and they are loose tolerance hole and most posts are slightly oversized.
b. I do not usually make the posts have the standard 19.05mm (3/4”) spacing between holes for dual plugs. I force single plugs since I don’t want one of my kids bridging different voltage lines. (I only made it 1mm different to mess with them though.. >:D )

7.) I used automotive wire terminals to connect everything. (Blade ends at the fuse box and circle ends at the posts)

8.) To mount it match drill using the fitting into the side of the psu and run two machine screws with a nut. (Bonus points if you use Loctite or a lock nut on the nut.)

This y-endstop is attached to the rear (or front) threaded rods of a Mendel type printer, e.g. by inserting its base between a vertex or rod clamp and its corresponding screw net. The endstop consists of a fixed base and a sliding arm onto which the endstop switch is mounted. The length of the slide and the position (horizontal/vertical) of the switch are configurable. The endstop can be mounted without disassembling the rods. It is stuck onto the lower threaded rod and then rotated along the circular cavity into the upper rod. The extension to the lower rod stabilizes the rotational position
the the endstop so that it won't rotate unintentionally around the upper rod. The switch holders have several screw hole slots that fit the standard 20x6mm micro-switches, which have screw holes which are spaced by 9.5mm. I found it easiest to extend the 2mm holes with a 2.5mm drill bit and then cut an M3 thread into them (using an M3 tap or just with a clean cut M3 screw). The STL files provided are for a standard sized Mendel (or any variant thereof, as is the Air-like version I use), which have M8 front and rear threaded rods that are spaced by 58.5mm at an angle of 60 degrees. For other dimensions, you need to modify the included SCAD file, where these parameters are parametrized. Note that for Prusa i3 type printers, you should use my sliding i3 Y-endstop. description.text:
Scoop designed for distributing powdered laundry detergent.

Interior mark half way up shows the average amount required for a full washing load.

I'm working on making some flair for the sides to be added on at the whim of the end user. I'm mostly done with a Deathguard plate, and I've started an Inquisitorial seal. You can probably also find fun things to affix by doing some searches. I know there is at least one purity seal.

The "Right Side" either prints with an unconscionable amount of bridging or almost entirely suspended in supports. Neither is a good situation, and I'm working on fixing it. My goal is extremely limited supports; we'll see how close I can get.

The largest dimension on the largest part is 127mm and the next smallest is 87mm or so, so if you can print 127x87, you should be able to make this. Sorry Select Mini users.

Additional sources for this model outside Thingiverse:
Tau Font from Kael'yn: http://www.advancedtautactica.com/viewtopic.php?t=18653
FMA24475 (Left Femur) from Body Parts 3D/Anatomography: http://lifesciencedb.jp/bp3d/?lng=en

0 - Dry-Fitting

There are a large number of tabs and slots here, and you will need to get them fitting - at the moment almost all of the parts are zero tolerance, so unless you are printing it solid or have a printer that is as exact as CAD software, these will not fit together. The upside is that anyone who would want to print this probably already has selection of plastic model files and sanding sticks.

You will probably also want to paint everything you want to paint and affix the exterior bling as you want before final assembly - that said, you don't want to have painted the box and then try to fit it because then you have to modify the parts to fit.

1 - Attach the sides to the baffles

If you stack the baffles up so that you can read the lettering on them, the "Top" will be furthest from you, and the "Bottom" closest. The bottoms of the baffles will slot into the "Left Side" and the tops will slot into the "Right Side". This is important because the middle baffle looks like the top baffle, except that it has an irregular spaced hole that attaches to the right side in order to avoid piercing exterior adornment (text).

The pin holes for the baffles are designed at 1mm diameter in order to properly fit the paperclips I have on my desk (0.8mm in diameter with the plastic sleeve removed). The hole is 10mm deep, so if you have an 9mm or shorter pin (I'd not go below 5mm though for strength) should be able to sit flush with the outside surface without bottoming out. If these are not the right size for your pins, you are probably the kind of person who owns a pin vice, so you can make them the right size. Or make new ones, or fill them with green stuff and not pin them at all. I wouldn't recommend not pinning the baffles, as these will be hit by lots of dice, lots of times, and you don't want them to come free; your dice tower may become a dice trap.

2 - Attach the front and back

Now you attach the front and back. Front goes such that the bottom baffle angles down to the opening. Back goes on the last side. Farsight logo has the top toward the right side (circle is the top of the logo) on both the front and back.

3 - Top and Bottom

Top goes on with the Farsight logo facing upward with the right side as the Tau top just like the Front and Back. This should put the dice opening toward the edge furthest from the opening on the Front. Bottom goes with the square pegs facing down and toward the dice opening in the front. This is where the dice tray attaches to the Base.

4 - DON'T glue the dice tray

Do not glue the dice tray onto the tower. It will be much easier if you leave the dice tray "loose" rather than affixed to the tower.

Primarily, transportation will be much simpler if there isn't a long and relatively delicate bit of plastic dangling off the side.

Secondarily, this is the part that will be hit with dice and touched by hands the most often. You will probably want to have a good thick clear-coat on this, and you may need to touch up the paint. Fixing any dice dings or rubbed off parts will be much easier if you can just deal with this part alone.

Tertiarily, I went out of my way to make the tray connections be full width even though the tray here could have done without just so that alternate trays could be made. Want a Nurgle tray? Kaela Mensha Khaine? Necron?

Quaternarily comes next, in case you are curious. It should really be quartarily, but biologists hosed that up with their using a slightly different word more often than normal people use the right word. There isn't really a 4th reason to not attach the tray, I just never get to use quaternarily. (I took 7 years of Latin).

title: Green laser with adjustable magnetic base.

description.text:
WARNING: A moron made a pitiful remix of it. A failure himself, he failed to understand its features, for ex. to be used with a spirit level. !
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Visible during daylight unlike red lasers. Handy for various alignment work. Paired with a good level, extends dramatically its possibilities, floor level, beam alignment, wall ....
In fact, I made this some time ago because my level red laser could not be seen when building a new terrace.
Use a rubber band to hold the switch if and when necessary. A sliding ring could be made to hold this switch. Green lasers eat batteries and are quite powerful. Use with caution, don't let them on all the time.

Can also be used to measure deflections, see vibrations etc in 3D printers for ex. Clamp or tape if necessary.

The laser (Diam 13mm, see Banggood, DX ... for the smallest green laser pointer) can be adjusted in elevation to align the magnetic base with the beam.

With a hacksaw finish the slit on the top (I did it this way to get a better cylinder). The base hole is for a 25x10x3 magnet (it is closed by a thin wall that needs to be cut, print vertically, no support). Superglue it making sure it protrudes slightly.
It it the surface reference, Indeed small but quite good as these magnets are well made.
I managed to adjust for 1mm/m error.
Secure the laser with two M2 X 8 screws
Use a M3 cap screw (flat tip). to adjust the elevation. Drill and tap accordingly (2.5mm hole is there !!!). Insert a steel shim on top of the screw tip. Rotate the laser if required.

PS: To avoid to print with support, hard to remove in small parts, I close holes with a thin wall (0.4mm) whenever possible. This lead to rather "clean" holes.

description.text:
This can be used to mount the female connector of a "Slim HDMI" cable in place of the Amiga RF modulator (which first needs to be removed from the motherboard). This provides easy access externally without having to cut the case or route the cable externally.

The "Slim HDMI" cable can be found here http://amzn.eu/0Ii7jV2

The two sections are held together using a cable tie, and then a second cable tie is used to attach it to the motherboard using the existing RF modulator holes. I also used to small piece of 3M tape on the bottom to stick it down.

Although this was designed with the Amiga 600 in mind, it should also be suitable for the Amiga 1200 once the Vampire V4 is released.

This is a simple and minimalistic PC build I built.

Tools:
Dremel or Hacksaw to cut the Screws in the right lenght
Soldering Iron

How to build:

The 2 mATX mounts where clicked together

PS Mount Mainboard support is mounted on the mainboard on the left under the varioud Ports (USB,...) with the Screw which also hold the mATX mount in place

On top of the mATX mount is screwd from top to bottom:
PS Mount
PS Mount PS-HDD Spacer
Drive Mount
Spacer ATXMount-DriveMount 26mm
mATX mount Bottom

The spacer "Spacer PCIPort-DriveMount 9mm" is glued in the middle of the 4 mounting Screws for the HDD-Drive on the "Drive Mount" in order to fill the gap between the "Drive Mount" and the PCI Ports on the Mainboard

Press fit the Tactile on its Mounting Part and screw it on of of the mounting Screws on the mainboard. Next you have to solder 2 wired to the coresponding pins on the tactile switch and the mainboard in order to turn on the computer.

My grandson has a ton of Nerf guns that shoot darts. We just bought him a Nerf gun that shoots the Nerf balls (if you haven't tried one of these guns, they hit way harder). I wanted him to have a good set of targets that were strong enough to handle the balls while still being fine with just the darts. I always find a use for wallyworld arrows, don't ask me why... :p

Anyway, I drew this up in Blender. The holes in the spinners are elongated to help the targets want to stay vertical when they reset after a shot. In the picture, I only used two of the 3 (inch) and one of the 4 (inch) spinners. You also need two spacers per spinner (Elmer's Purple Glue holds the spacers where you want them). Two brackets for the ends, 5 shafts and 2 preferably old CDs or DVDs per spinner (glued in). I covered all the CDs on both sides with blank CD labels and my grandson painted all the centers of the labels red to make the bullseyes.This time the shafts I procured were .292" diameter, so I made all the holes .310". Scale your parts accordingly.

Edit 8/23/2017: Now that we've played with this enough... The current design is great for any of the Nerf Darts. If you're using the Nerf Balls, put 3 layers of CD Labels on each side. If you don't, they'll break the CDs pretty quick. Those balls are just too tough for the CD/DVDs even with a layer of paper on both sides. So... I'm doing a remix design that won't break (so easily) with the Nerf Balls.

description.text:
I looked quite a bit but didn't find any delta effector mounts that I liked for an auto bed levelling sensor. The few I found were either too long, or didn't fit the thickness of my aluminum effector plate. I decided to try to learn Fusion 360 and make my own, and here is the result of my first F360 project.

I'm using the aluminum "End Effector for Kossel" from Robotdigg. It's the one they show with the square cutouts between the arm mounting points (which is where this thing slips in to).

The original version has a 3mm thick mounting plate to hold the sensor up. I have added a v2 version which bumps that to 5mm thick, which should be a bit stiffer.

The Fusion file is included, in case anyone needs to make changes.
